SIMPLE: work
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Work
<hw>Work</hw> <pr>(w⟦ucir⟧rk)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>work</ets>, <ets>werk</ets>, <ets>weorc</ets>, AS.
<ets>weorc</ets>, <ets>worc</ets>; akin to OFries. <ets>werk</ets>,
<ets>wirk</ets>, OS., D., & G. <ets>werk</ets>, OHG. <ets>werc</ets>,
<ets>werah</ets>, Icel. & Sw. <ets>verk</ets>, Dan. <ets>v⟦ae⟧rk</ets>,
Goth. ga<ets>wa⟦uacute⟧rki</ets>, Gr. <grk>'e`rgon</grk>,
⟦digamma⟧<grk>e`rgon</grk>, work, <grk>"re`zein</grk> to do,
<grk>'o`rganon</grk> an instrument, <grk>'o`rgia</grk> secret rites,
Zend <ets>verez</ets> to work. ⟦root⟧145. Cf. <er>Bulwark</er>,
<er>Energy</er>, <er>Erg</er>, <er>Georgic</er>, <er>Liturgy</er>,
<er>Metallurgy</er>, <er>Organ</er>, <er>Orgy</er>, <er>Surgeon</er>,
<er>Wright</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Exertion of strength or faculties; physical or
intellectual effort directed to an end; industrial activity; toil;
employment; sometimes, specifically, physical labor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Man hath his daily <qex>work</qex> of body or mind⟦br⟧
Appointed.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The matter on which one is at work; that upon which
one spends labor; material for working upon; subject of exertion; the
thing occupying one; business; duty; <as>as, to take up one's
<ex>work</ex>; to drop one's <ex>work</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Come on, Nerissa; I have <qex>work</qex> in hand⟦br⟧
That you yet know not of.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In every <qex>work</qex> that he began . . . he did it with all
his heart, and prospered.</q> <rj><qau>2 Chron. xxxi. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is produced as the result of labor;
anything accomplished by exertion or toil; product; performance; fabric;
manufacture; in a more general sense, act, deed, service, effect,
result, achievement, feat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To leave no rubs or blotches in the <qex>work</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>work</qex> some praise,⟦br⟧
And some the architect.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fancy . . . ⟦br⟧
Wild <qex>work</qex> produces oft, and most in dreams.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The composition or dissolution of mixed bodies . . . is the chief
<qex>work</qex> of elements.</q> <rj><qau>Sir K. Digby.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Specifically: <sd>(a)</sd> That which is produced by
mental labor; a composition; a book; <as>as, a <ex>work</ex>, or the
<ex>works</ex>, of Addison</as>. <sd>(b)</sd> Flowers, figures, or the
like, wrought with the needle; embroidery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am glad I have found this napkin; . . . ⟦br⟧
I'll have the <qex>work</qex> ta'en out,⟦br⟧
And give 't Iago.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Structures in civil, military, or
naval engineering, as docks, bridges, embankments, trenches,
fortifications, and the like; also, the structures and grounds of a
manufacturing establishment; <as>as, iron <ex>works</ex>; locomotive
<ex>works</ex>; gas <ex>works</ex></as>.</def> <sd>(d)</sd>
<pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The moving parts of a mechanism; as, the
<xex>works</xex> of a watch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Manner of working; management; treatment; <as>as,
unskillful <ex>work</ex> spoiled the effect</as>.</def> <rj><au>Bp.
Stillingfleet.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>The causing of motion against a
resisting force. The amount of work is proportioned to, and is measured
by, the product of the force into the amount of motion along the
direction of the force. See <cref>Conservation of energy</cref>, under
<er>Conservation</er>, <cref>Unit of work</cref>, under <er>Unit</er>,
also <er>Foot pound</er>, <er>Horse power</er>, <er>Poundal</er>, and
<er>Erg</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Energy is the capacity of doing <qex>work</qex> . . .
<qex>Work</qex> is the transference of energy from one system to
another.</q> <rj><qau>Clerk Maxwell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>Ore before it is dressed.</def>
<rj><au>Raymond.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Script.)</fld> <def>Performance of
moral duties; righteous conduct.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He shall reward every man according to his <qex>works</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. xvi. 27.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Faith, if it hath not <qex>works</qex>, is dead.</q>
<rj><qau>James ii. 17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Cricket)</fld> <def>Break; twist.</def>
<mark>[Cant]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>The causing of motion against a
resisting force, measured by the product of the force into the component
of the motion resolved along the direction of the force.</def></p>

<p><q>Energy is the capacity of doing <qex>work</qex>. . . .
<qex>Work</qex> is the transference of energy from one system to
another.</q> <rj><qau>Clerk Maxwell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>Ore before it is
dressed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Muscular work</b></col> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld>, <cd>the
work done by a muscle through the power of contraction.</cd> --
<col><b>To go to work</b></col>, <cd>to begin laboring; to commence
operations; to contrive; to manage.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧I 'll <xex>go</xex>
another way <xex>to work</xex> with him.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> --
<col><b>To set on work</b></col>, <cd>to cause to begin laboring; to set
to work.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Hooker.</au> -- <col><b>To set to
work</b></col>, <cd>to employ; to cause to engage in any business or
labor.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Work</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Work
<hw>Work</hw> <pr>(w⟦ucir⟧rk)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Worked</conjf> <pr>(w⟦ucir⟧rkt)</pr>, or
<conjf>Wrought</conjf> <pr>(r⟦add⟧t)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Working</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>wyrcean</ets> (imp.
<ets>worthe</ets>, <ets>wrohte</ets>, p. p. <ets>geworht</ets>,
<ets>gewroht</ets>); akin to OFries. <ets>werka</ets>, <ets>wirka</ets>,
OS. <ets>wirkian</ets>, D. <ets>werken</ets>, G. <ets>wirken</ets>,
Icel. <ets>verka</ets>, <ets>yrkja</ets>, <ets>orka</ets>, Goth.
<ets>wa⟦uacute⟧rkjan</ets>. ⟦root⟧145. See <er>Work</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To exert one's self for a purpose; to put forth
effort for the attainment of an object; to labor; to be engaged in the
performance of a task, a duty, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O thou good Kent, how shall I live and <qex>work</qex>,⟦br⟧
To match thy goodness?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Go therefore now, and <qex>work</qex>; for there shall no straw be
given you.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. v. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whether we <qex>work</qex> or play, or sleep or wake,⟦br⟧
Our life doth pass.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J. Davies.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, in a general sense, to operate; to act; to
perform; <as>as, a machine <ex>works</ex> well</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We bend to that the <qex>working</qex> of the heart.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, figuratively, to be effective; to have effect
or influence; to conduce.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We know that all things <qex>work</qex> together for good to them
that love God.</q> <rj><qau>Rom. viii. 28.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This so <qex>wrought</qex> upon the child, that afterwards he
desired to be taught.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She marveled how she could ever have been <qex>wrought</qex> upon
to marry him.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To carry on business; to be engaged or employed
customarily; to perform the part of a laborer; to labor; to
toil.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They that <qex>work</qex> in fine flax . . . shall be
confounded.</q> <rj><qau>Isa. xix. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To be in a state of severe exertion, or as if in
such a state; to be tossed or agitated; to move heavily; to strain; to
labor; <as>as, a ship <ex>works</ex> in a heavy sea</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Confused with <qex>working</qex> sands and rolling waves.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To make one's way slowly and with difficulty; to
move or penetrate laboriously; to proceed with effort; -- with a
following preposition, as <xex>down</xex>, <xex>out</xex>,
<xex>into</xex>, <xex>up</xex>, <xex>through</xex>, and the like;
<as>as, scheme <ex>works</ex> out by degrees; to <ex>work</ex> into the
earth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Till body up to spirit <qex>work</qex>, in bounds⟦br⟧
Proportioned to each kind.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To ferment, as a liquid.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>working</qex> of beer when the barm is put in.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To act or operate on the stomach and bowels, as a
cathartic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Purges . . . <qex>work</qex> best, that is, cause the blood so to
do, . . . in warm weather or in a warm room.</q>
<rj><qau>Grew.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1665 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To work at</b></col>, <cd>to be engaged in or upon; to be
employed in.</cd> -- <col><b>To work to windward</b></col>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to sail or ply against the wind; to tack to
windward.</cd> <rj><au>Mar. Dict.</au></rj> </cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Work</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Work
<hw>Work</hw> <pr>(w⟦ucir⟧rk)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
labor or operate upon; to give exertion and effort to; to prepare for
use, or to utilize, by labor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He could have told them of two or three gold mines, and a silver
mine, and given the reason why they forbare to <qex>work</qex> them at
that time.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To produce or form by labor; to bring forth by
exertion or toil; to accomplish; to originate; to effect; <as>as, to
<ex>work</ex> wood or iron into a form desired, or into a utensil; to
<ex>work</ex> cotton or wool into cloth.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Each herb he knew, that <qex>works</qex> or good or ill.</q>
<rj><qau>Harte.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To produce by slow degrees, or as if laboriously; to
bring gradually into any state by action or motion.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Sidelong he <xex>works</xex> his way.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So the pure, limpid stream, when foul with stains⟦br⟧
Of rushing torrents and descending rains,⟦br⟧
<qex>Works</qex> itself clear, and as it runs, refines,⟦br⟧
Till by degrees the floating mirror shines.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To influence by acting upon; to prevail upon; to
manage; to lead.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Work</xex> your royal father to his
ruin.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Philips.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To form with a needle and thread or yarn;
especially, to embroider; <as>as, to <ex>work</ex>
muslin</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To set in motion or action; to direct the action of;
to keep at work; to govern; to manage; <as>as, to <ex>work</ex> a
machine</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Knowledge in building and <qex>working</qex> ships.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now, Marcus, thy virtue's the proof;⟦br⟧
Put forth thy utmost strength, <qex>work</qex> every nerve.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The mariners all 'gan <qex>work</qex> the ropes,⟦br⟧
Where they were wont to do.</q> <rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To cause to ferment, as liquor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>To work a passage</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to
pay for a passage by doing work.</cd> -- <col><b>To work double
tides</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to perform the labor of three
days in two; -- a phrase which alludes to a practice of working by the
night tide as well as by the day.</cd> -- <col><b>To work in</b></col>,
<cd>to insert, introduce, mingle, or interweave by labor or skill.</cd>
-- <col><b>To work into</b></col>, <cd>to force, urge, or insinuate
into; <as>as, <ex>to work</ex> one's self <ex>into</ex> favor or
confidence</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To work off</b></col>, <cd>to remove
gradually, as by labor, or a gradual process; <as>as, beer <ex>works
off</ex> impurities in fermenting</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To work
out</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To effect by labor and exertion.</cd>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Work out</xex> your own salvation with fear and
trembling.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Phil. ii. 12.</au> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To erase; to
efface.</cd> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tears of joy for your returning spilt,⟦br⟧
<qex>Work out</qex> and expiate our former guilt.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <cd>To solve, as a problem.</cd> <sd>(d)</sd> <cd>To
exhaust, as a mine, by working.</cd> -- <col><b>To work up</b></col>.
<sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To raise; to excite; to stir up; as, <xex>to work
up</xex> the passions to rage.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sun, that rolls his chariot o'er their heads,⟦br⟧
<qex>Works up</qex> more fire and color in their cheeks.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To expend in any work, as materials; as, they have
<xex>worked up</xex> all the stock.</cd> <sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>
<cd>To make over or into something else, as yarns drawn from old
rigging, made into spun yarn, foxes, sennit, and the like; also, to keep
constantly at work upon needless matters, as a crew in order to punish
them.</cd> <au>R. H. Dana, Jr.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Workable</ent>⟦br⟧
